messages:
[{'account_id': 28522, 'date': '2021-06-01 09:00:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Cherry Picked from branch master.'}, {'account_id': 27339, 'date': '2021-06-01 09:19:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Can be then'}, {'account_id': 27339, 'date': '2021-06-01 09:21:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Herve, I don't know how release is processed, but can be this included in https://releases.openstack.org/wallaby/ as bump keystonemiddleware version ?"}, {'account_id': 28522, 'date': '2021-06-01 11:41:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> Herve, I don't know how release is processed, but can be this included in https://releases.openstack.org/wallaby/ as bump keystonemiddleware version ?

If these changes will be merged then yes we will release them for wallaby and for the other stable branches.

I added Elod to the reviewers, he is stable maintainer.

We observed many similar related cases downstream and the switching the option in the configuration helped us to ride away of this issue. Hopefully these changes will be merged."}, {'account_id': 28522, 'date': '2021-06-01 11:49:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Patch Set 1 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 17685, 'date': '2021-06-01 13:39:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

As I understand this patch changes default configuration, which is considered an 'incompatible configuration change' and that is not allowed according to stable policy [1].
(Sorry Hervé, I did not realized this at first glance)

Fortunately, as I understand the workaround, to fix the mentioned bugs, is pretty easy and can be solved with the very same configuration change.

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/project-team-guide/stable-branches.html#review-guidelines"}, {'account_id': 28522, 'date': '2021-06-01 14:23:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Thanks Elod for your opinion.

I agree that that will change the default configuration, unfortunatelly the default configuration led to memcached connections issues and performance degradations. In other words the default config doesn't work and lead to errors.

I agree that this problem can be fixed by passing the right config, unfortunatelly lot of downstream customers need to update all their environments to fix the issue.

Switching the options will allow us to be proactive and will allow downstream maintainers to spread the fix with minor upgrade, without requiring lot of maintenance (template updates, hiera keys, etc) from users/operators.

Also we should notice that keystonemiddleware's cache module is a bit outdated and that switching the option will replace it by a well know backend already in openstack/oslo.cache since awhile.

As discussed with you (Elod) I Adding Sean to get his feedback too."}, {'account_id': 27339, 'date': '2022-07-12 18:32:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 27339, 'date': '2022-07-12 18:33:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2021-06-01 09:00:17.000000000', 'message': 'Switch to eventlet-safe oslo.cache's MemcacheClientPool

In past days there were discussions about various issues
with memcached connections [1][2][3].

After investigation it looks like common root cause for above
problems is keystonemiddleware. More precisely said the way
how keystonemiddleware is caching tokens.

Currently it's using some home-made CachePool with direct
usage of memcached library, moreover it looks like its
approach is not eventlet-safe.
Discussion can be mainly found in [4].

Fortunately keystonemiddleware can use "advanced cache pool",
which is oslo.cache's implementation and was added long time ago [5],
but it is turned on only if memcache_use_advanced_pool=True.

This patch is switching to more elaborated oslo.cache CachePool
and adding deprecation warning about eventlet-unsafe variant
of keystonemiddleware's memcache pool.

How to reproduce ?

with memcache_use_advanced_pool=False

1. Build clean ENV of openstack

commit_message:
Switch to eventlet-safe oslo.cache's MemcacheClientPool

In past days there were discussions about various issues
with memcached connections [1][2][3].

After investigation it looks like common root cause for above
problems is keystonemiddleware. More precisely said the way
how keystonemiddleware is caching tokens.

Currently it's using some home-made CachePool with direct
usage of memcached library, moreover it looks like its
approach is not eventlet-safe.
Discussion can be mainly found in [4].

Fortunately keystonemiddleware can use "advanced cache pool",
which is oslo.cache's implementation and was added long time ago [5],
but it is turned on only if memcache_use_advanced_pool=True.

This patch is switching to more elaborated oslo.cache CachePool
and adding deprecation warning about eventlet-unsafe variant
of keystonemiddleware's memcache pool.

How to reproduce ?

with memcache_use_advanced_pool=False

1. Build clean ENV of openstack
2. Deploy core projects (keystone,glance,nova,placement...)
3. Run while true; do COMMAND FOR SERVICE; done
   - several bashes, in parallel (5-7)

COMMAND FOR SERVICE:
- openstack network list
- openstack volume list
- openstack server list
- openstack image list

4. Check memcached connections (which will grow up):
    - ss | grep 11211 | wc -l   every second

How to fix and test it ?

Repeat above, to fix:
 - with memcache_use_advanced_pool=True
   OR
 - apply this patch

Compare measurements in graph.

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/keystonemiddleware/+bug/1892852
[2] https://bugs.launchpad.net/oslo.cache/+bug/1888394
[3] https://bugs.launchpad.net/keystonemiddleware/+bug/1883659

[4] https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/oslo.cache/+/742193

[5] https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/keystonemiddleware/+/268664

Closes-Bug: #1883659
Closes-Bug: #1892852
Closes-Bug: #1888394

Change-Id: I0e96334b65a0bf369ebf1d88651d13feb8d2ecac
(cherry picked from commit 788d3c4969e3446778496f3a9055f654602ae2c1)

commit_message:
[collectd] Remove processes plugin from default list

Remove the processes plugin from the default collectd plugins list as it
can cause logging to be flooded with messages such as 'procs_running not
found'.

Change-Id: I740a87bdf9ce9fccc34e661c48053ac8c969b5db
Signed-off-by: Leif Madsen <lmadsen@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit 91ee65408e6f4eb70338b42bc7c3791272c14dbd)

commit_message:
Run package check for openstack-selinux in privileged mode

rpm -V command needs to be run as root for some packages.
The current script fails with openstack-selinux package, which is included in tripleo_bootstrap_packages_bootstrap.

Closes-Bug: #1981353

Remove _create_subnet & create_networks methods

As tempest.scenario.manager was announced stable interface in Tempest 27.0.0[1] it can be now reused in plugins.

Replaced methods:
	* _create_subnet
	* create_networks (not used)

Etherpad concerning this effort:
https://etherpad.opendev.org/p/tempest-scenario-manager-cleanup

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/releasenotes/tempest/v27.0.0.html#release-notes-27-0-0

[{'created': '2022-07-12 08:03:50.000000000', 'message': "zuul: Put Centos9 Stream job periodic-weekly and experimental

This patch is a followup on 45c0a3884b6b4c0b9a6b1b3cef47651f5504502e

As agreed on the Nova weekly meeting [1], we won't put back C9S job to voting
and we'll rather put it on both experimental and periodic-weekly pipelines.
In order to insure we will monitor the status of those runs, we'll check
the status of the job during every Nova meeting happening weekly.

In order to trigger potential race conditions, it was acted to provide an
experimental job for C9S too.

[1] https://meetings.opendev.org/meetings/nova/2022/nova.2022-07-05-16.00.log.html#l-52

Change-Id: I2de4d90202fd7e735026150f79409d51f2d70e0e
"}]
commit_message:
zuul: Put Centos9 Stream job periodic-weekly and experimental

This patch is a followup on 45c0a3884b6b4c0b9a6b1b3cef47651f5504502e

As agreed on the Nova weekly meeting [1], we won't put back C9S job to voting
and we'll rather put it on both experimental and periodic-weekly pipelines.
In order to insure we will monitor the status of those runs, we'll check
the status of the job during every Nova meeting happening weekly.

In order to trigger potential race conditions, it was acted to provide an
experimental job for C9S too.

[1] https://meetings.opendev.org/meetings/nova/2022/nova.2022-07-05-16.00.log.html#l-52

Change-Id: I2de4d90202fd7e735026150f79409d51f2d70e0e

commit_message:
Remove redundant apache::default_vhost

The parameter is set by the base apache service resource since [1] was
merged. Also, the definition in heat-engine service is useless because
the service does not require httpd.

This is an unusual API. In theory, it should support the list and detail
operations but these are actually two totally different APIs. The list
operation ('GET /os-hosts') returns a list of hosts on which any

etc. - is running:

  {
    "hosts": [
      {
        "service-status": "available",
        "service": "cinder-backup",
        "zone": "nova",
        "service-state": "enabled",
        "host_name": "node1",
        "last-update": "2017-03-09T21:38:41.000000"
      },
      ...
    ]
  }

While the detail operation ('GET /os-hosts/{hostname}') returns a list
of hosts associated with an instance of a 'cinder-volume' service:

  {
    "host": [
      {
            "resource": {
                "volume_count": "8",
                "total_volume_gb": "11",

                "project": "(total)",
                "host": "node1@rbd-sas",
                "snapshot_count": "1"
            }
      },
      ...
    ]
  }

These should really have been separate APIs since they're radically
different things, and I guess the cinder developers realized as much
this since the API issues a deprecation warning when used. In any case,
we have to work around this by presenting two different APIs.

commit_message:
blockstorage: Add Host Resource

This is an unusual API. In theory, it should support the list and detail
operations but these are actually two totally different APIs. The list
operation ('GET /os-hosts') returns a list of hosts on which any
cinder-related service - cinder-backup, cinder-scheduler, cinder-volume,
etc. - is running:

  {
    "hosts": [
      {
        "service-status": "available",
        "service": "cinder-backup",
        "zone": "nova",
        "service-state": "enabled",
        "host_name": "node1",
        "last-update": "2017-03-09T21:38:41.000000"
      },
      ...
    ]
  }

While the detail operation ('GET /os-hosts/{hostname}') returns a list
of hosts associated with an instance of a 'cinder-volume' service:

  {
    "host": [
      {
            "resource": {
                "volume_count": "8",
                "total_volume_gb": "11",
                "total_snapshot_gb": "1",
                "project": "(total)",
                "host": "node1@rbd-sas",
                "snapshot_count": "1"
            }
      },
      ...
    ]
  }

These should really have been separate APIs since they're radically
different things, and I guess the cinder developers realized as much
this since the API issues a deprecation warning when used. In any case,
we have to work around this by presenting two different APIs.

Change-Id: I68956431b804ab8d464d530e3ffd7c5f7776eb42
Task: 41815
Story: 2008619

messages:
[{'account_id': 33036, 'date': '2021-06-27 14:47:41.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 33036, 'date': '2021-06-27 15:33:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(3 comments)

Hi all,

Here's my first draft of the workers resource and its cleanup method (both incomplete). My understanding of how the Workers resource should be implemented is as follows:

1. block_storage.v3.Proxy.workers_cleanup (from _proxy.py) is called (either by the OpenStackClient or end user?), with the requested filtering criteria passed via the **attrs dictionary.

2. In the workers_cleanup resource: An empty Worker resource/object is instantiated. Then the cleanup method of the worker object is called, and the requested filtering criteria is passed via the **attrs dictionary (again).

3. In the cleanup method of the Workers object: the **attrs dictionary is validated. From here I believe another API request is made to actually clean the requested services (akin to https://opendev.org/openstack/openstacksdk/src/branch/master/openstack/block_storage/v3/volume.py#L112 ), but I'm not sure what the URL/endpoint is.

Could one of you ensure that my understanding is correct? If my explanation is ambiguous or flawed please let me know. Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 33036, 'date': '2022-04-24 23:21:49.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 15334, 'date': '2022-07-12 16:44:08.000000000', 'content': 'Topic workers removed'}, {'account_id': 15334, 'date': '2022-07-12 16:44:10.000000000', 'content': 'Topic set to ndsu-capstone'}, {'account_id': 15334, 'date': '2022-07-12 16:44:56.000000000', 'content': 'Topic ndsu-capstone removed'}, {'account_id': 15334, 'date': '2022-07-12 16:44:57.000000000', 'content': 'Topic set to cinder-gaps'}]

commit_message:
WIP: conductor worker mode

A basic idea of what it might look like to provide a
worker mode flag to help short cirucit some of the
conductor logic and allow an operator to run with greater
CPU concurrency by beginning to split apart the ironic
conductor process.

This should kind of serve as a first conceptual idea of
what we could do in an iterrative fashion to improve
locking and concurrency.

Change-Id: I60be5b09b0c91cc4c03e2e2b4deb1645e352eaac

commit_message:
ubuntu: more exact match on squashfs file, containerfile: use focal

This is a squash of two changes that have unfortunately simultaneously
broken the gate.

The functests are failing with

 sha256sum: bionic-server-cloudimg-amd64.squashfs.manifest: No such file or directory

I think what has happened here is that the SHA256 sums file being used
has got a new entry "bionic-server-cloudimg-amd64.squashfs.manifest"
which is showing up in a grep for
"bionic-server-cloudimg-amd64.squashfs".  sha256 then tries to also
check this hash, and has started failing.

To avoid this, add an EOL marker to the grep so it only matches the
exact filename.

Change I7fb585bc5ccc52803eea107e76dddf5e9fde8646 updated the
containerfile tests to Jammy and it seems that cgroups v2 prevents
podman running inside docker [1].  While we investigate, move this
testing back to focal.

[1] https://github.com/containers/podman/issues/14884
Change-Id: I1af9f5599168aadc1e7fcdfae281935e6211a597

commit_message:
Make allowed_cidrs optional for listener

An additional parameter test_allowed_cidrs has been
added to allow the execution of tests using it or not
on creation/updating listeners. By default this
parameter will be load True.

commit_message:
Handle tripleo_ceph_deploy_container_namespace per scenario

I1abfbbd23ca93c01393d05057806ba9cc846fbed fixed LP 1978998
by having the tripleo_ceph_deploy role get its container
not from an unavailable undercloud registry but from
quay.rdoproject.org. That avoids one problem but breaks
tripleo-ci-centos-9-scenario00{1,4}-ceph-nightly periodic
since quay.rdoproject.org/tripleomastercentos9 does not
have daemon:latest-pacific-devel which causes LP 1981329.

As per https://review.rdoproject.org/r/c/rdo-jobs/+/42583,
we need tripleo-ci-centos-9-scenario00{1,4}-ceph-nightly to
use quay.io/ceph/daemon:latest and the container vars are
already set correctly.

Set tripleo_ceph_deploy_container_namespace correctly per
scenario with a new task to detect the scenario and set
it accordingly.

Change-Id: I3bff2e0b6930dfbbbd1ce01265f40e70df753128
Closes-Bug: #1981329

commit_message:
Use cloudsmith repo for rabbit and erlang

Switch to using cloudsmith repo as a source for rabbitmq and erlang.

This allows us to be consistent about repository that is
used across supported distributions along with switching from
unreliable erlang-solutions that tend to fail periodically.

Change-Id: Ia438ee3b0aa1ba95aff014776e936516b83181ec
(cherry picked from commit 4ab856bfefd07ca5fb39d66c93530e9b7ab0fe76)

commit_message:
No deploy_kernel/ramdisk with the ramdisk deploy and no cleaning

Ramdisk deploys don't use IPA, no need to provide it. Cleaning may need
the agent, so only skip verification if cleaning is disabled.

Other boot interfaces may need fixing as well, I haven't checked them.

Change-Id: Ia2739311f065e19ba539fe3df7268075d6075787
(cherry picked from commit 65583e64172a0188d125117d1f2288e105832395)

subject: Improve string representation of DB models
messages: [{'account_id': 34429, 'date': '2022-06-27 08:37:54.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 34429, 'date': '2022-07-12 15:28:19.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned\n\nbackporting not to victoria'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2022-06-27 08:37:54.000000000', 'message': 'Improve string representation of DB models

This replaces the default "<XYClass object at 0xdeadbeeff00>"
repr() for DB objects, which is pretty useless.
This change makes it easier to identify DB objects in debuggers
(and logs, if objects get logged).

__repr__() and __str__() have slightly different purposes.

The purpose of __repr__() is to return a string that uniquely identifies
a single object. __str__(), on the other hand, should produce a human
readable string. Another thing that is worth to note is that str() will
call __repr__() if __str__() is not implemented, repr() will always call
__repr__(). More details can be found under [1].

By implementing a generic __repr__() in the base class
there should be no need to override it in the models classes.
However, one might not be interested in seeing all
the object's attributes in a string representation
(which is what the generic __repr__() would do) or
certain sensitive information should be hidden from users.
In those cases it makes sense to implement __str__() for certain
classes specifically.

[1]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/2626364/6265131

Change-Id: I4c218793948b0ed7ce0c143d6c794516fdeb224f
(cherry picked from commit ff6d0c5280fbdbe8f5361469fb88448fa650f365)
(cherry picked from commit bc95e34819bed67444c752e59c01a90c0c6df89b)
(cherry picked from commit 77c86a2409a7e244c713a6d680d2d38f9f6e7bbd)
(cherry picked from commit b55247d1feaa99b7b383a0a41e1685b57a547678)
'}]
commit_message:
Improve string representation of DB models

This replaces the default "<XYClass object at 0xdeadbeeff00>"
repr() for DB objects, which is pretty useless.
This change makes it easier to identify DB objects in debuggers
(and logs, if objects get logged).

__repr__() and __str__() have slightly different purposes.

The purpose of __repr__() is to return a string that uniquely identifies
a single object. __str__(), on the other hand, should produce a human
readable string. Another thing that is worth to note is that str() will
call __repr__() if __str__() is not implemented, repr() will always call
__repr__(). More details can be found under [1].

By implementing a generic __repr__() in the base class
there should be no need to override it in the models classes.
However, one might not be interested in seeing all
the object's attributes in a string representation
(which is what the generic __repr__() would do) or
certain sensitive information should be hidden from users.
In those cases it makes sense to implement __str__() for certain
classes specifically.

[1]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/2626364/6265131

Change-Id: I4c218793948b0ed7ce0c143d6c794516fdeb224f
(cherry picked from commit ff6d0c5280fbdbe8f5361469fb88448fa650f365)
(cherry picked from commit bc95e34819bed67444c752e59c01a90c0c6df89b)
(cherry picked from commit 77c86a2409a7e244c713a6d680d2d38f9f6e7bbd)
(cherry picked from commit b55247d1feaa99b7b383a0a41e1685b57a547678)

revisions:
[{'created': '2022-07-07 23:19:54.000000000', 'message': "Do a precise node lookup for unprovision

A hostname or name is passed to the unprovision call, and the node is
looked up by allocation name (hostname), falling back to node name.

This can result in the wrong node being unprovisioned in the following
scenario:
* node and hostname naming scheme are identical
* node and hostname names are mixed because allocation placement
  doesn't take the node name into account
* a node has already been unprovisioned by hostname (allocation)
  lookup
* unprovision is performed a second time, this time matching the
  hostname with a different node's name
* the wrong node is unprovisioned

The unprovision_node method can also take a node object instead of a
string identifier, so this change does a precise node lookup before
calling it. This means only hostnames are used for allocation lookups,
and node names for node lookups.

Change-Id: I9507f8d30c871ae62a250148789393695d59183a
Resolves: rhbz#2092444

Resolves: rhbz#2092444

commit_message:
Do a precise node lookup for unprovision

A hostname or name is passed to the unprovision call, and the node is
looked up by allocation name (hostname), falling back to node name.

This can result in the wrong node being unprovisioned in the following
scenario:
* node and hostname naming scheme are identical
* node and hostname names are mixed because allocation placement
  doesn't take the node name into account
* a node has already been unprovisioned by hostname (allocation)
  lookup
* unprovision is performed a second time, this time matching the
  hostname with a different node's name
* the wrong node is unprovisioned

The unprovision_node method can also take a node object instead of a
string identifier, so this change does a precise node lookup before
calling it. This means only hostnames are used for allocation lookups,
and node names for node lookups.

Change-Id: I9507f8d30c871ae62a250148789393695d59183a
Resolves: rhbz#2092444

commit_message:
Set default block.db size based on osd device size

Default value of block.db (bluestore_block_db_size) is set
to 1024. However, this may end up being lower than the
recommended size of 4%. This change sets the block.db size
as the 4% of the osd device size.

Change-Id: I3f0515ce7cdbefb7a21c28fc3891f4c6a20bec5d
Closes-Bug: 1827463

Existing ones use sha1 which some openssl distributions refuse to verify
due to being obsolete and not FIPS compliant, leading to failing unit

'}]
commit_message:
Regenerate example certificates using sha256 digest algorithm

Existing ones use sha1 which some openssl distributions refuse to verify
due to being obsolete and not FIPS compliant, leading to failing unit
tests.

Regenerating them using sha256 as the digest algorithm allows unit tests
to pass again.

Closes-Bug: #1981451
Change-Id: Ic34019e9c9742dafa67748e0c16b768893269339

[{'created': '2022-06-15 16:37:47.000000000', 'message': '[OVN] Sync QoS policies

The tool "neutron-ovn-db-sync-util" now syncs the Neutron QoS policies
with the OVN NB database. The tools reads the port and the floaiting IP
QoS policies and creates the corresponding OVN QoS rules.

The ovsdbapp library is bumped to version 1.15.0. This version updates
the "QoSAddCommand" to allow register updates. If the OVN NB QoS
register to be created is present in the DB and all parameters match,
no transaction is commited to the DB.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/ovsdbapp/+/822138
Closes-Bug: #1947334

Conflicts:
    lower-constraints.txt
    neutron/plugins/ml2/drivers/ovn/mech_driver/ovsdb/extensions/qos.py
    neutron/plugins/ml2/drivers/ovn/mech_driver/ovsdb/ovn_client.py
    neutron/plugins/ml2/drivers/ovn/mech_driver/ovsdb/ovn_db_sync.py
    neutron/tests/unit/plugins/ml2/drivers/ovn/mech_driver/ovsdb/extensions/test_qos.py
    requirements.txt

Change-Id: Ib597b62017b56b41009dd4d7359e169f424272b0

commit_message:
[OVN] Sync QoS policies

The tool "neutron-ovn-db-sync-util" now syncs the Neutron QoS policies
with the OVN NB database. The tools reads the port and the floaiting IP
QoS policies and creates the corresponding OVN QoS rules.

The ovsdbapp library is bumped to version 1.15.0. This version updates
the "QoSAddCommand" to allow register updates. If the OVN NB QoS
register to be created is present in the DB and all parameters match,
no transaction is commited to the DB.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/ovsdbapp/+/822138
Closes-Bug: #1947334

Conflicts:
    lower-constraints.txt
    neutron/plugins/ml2/drivers/ovn/mech_driver/ovsdb/extensions/qos.py
    neutron/plugins/ml2/drivers/ovn/mech_driver/ovsdb/ovn_client.py
    neutron/plugins/ml2/drivers/ovn/mech_driver/ovsdb/ovn_db_sync.py
    neutron/tests/unit/plugins/ml2/drivers/ovn/mech_driver/ovsdb/extensions/test_qos.py
    requirements.txt

Change-Id: Ib597b62017b56b41009dd4d7359e169f424272b0
(cherry picked from commit cde5657a504f6658cb1c9c98235c120030f86130)

commit_message:
[wip] Build a dib reference image

Making dib able to build everything of interest requires a bit of
external setup, and we only really validate it in one environment.
Traditionally this has been the same environment as nodepool-builder,
since that's what dib runs under in production.

To avoid having to duplicate fixes and avoid version skew, we've
avoided making a dib reference container that just contains dib.
However, there is some interest in moving image builds to be trigger
directly by Zuul jobs rather than nodepool-builder.  In that case, we
would want to run dib from it's own validated environment.  This
builds a container image the same as the nodepool-builder Debian
bullsye environment, incorporating the various bits from the nodepool
container seutp.

Change-Id: Ief1aae0b7f4215f0e77cfe49d2ac10cc9989d0fc

commit_message:
Set sensible nf_conntrack_max value in amphora

This sets the values of nf_conntrack_max and nf_conntrack_expect_max to
sensible values. Previously, the default values set by the kernel were
used, which limited net.netfilter.nf_conntrack_max to 32768. On the
other hand, Octavia sets nf_conntrack_buckets to 125000. A value of
nf_conntrack_max lower than half of that makes no sense.

The new values are calculated using the formula for the default value
in the kernel [1]:

nf_conntrack_max = nf_conntrack_buckets
nf_conntrack_expect_max = nf_conntrack_buckets / 256

[1]: https://www.kernel.org/doc/Documentation/networking/nf_conntrack-sysctl.rst

commit_message:
Set minimal tempest version to 27.0.0

As tempest.scenario.manager was announced stable interface in Tempest
27.0.0[1] it can be now reused in plugins.

Some methods replaced in scenario-manager-cleanup effort won't work
with tempest version lower than 27.0.0 therefore minimal tempest
version must be updated in tempest plugins

Etherpad concerning this effort:
https://etherpad.opendev.org/p/tempest-scenario-manager-cleanup

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/releasenotes/tempest/v27.0.0.html#release-notes-27-0-0

Change-Id: I422435abd4fb34fbba187deb0d96ef314767ff19

Remove create_server and rebuild_server methods

As tempest.scenario.manager was announced stable interface in Tempest 27.0.0[1] it can be now reused in plugins.

Replaced methods:
	* create_server
	* rebuild_server

https://etherpad.opendev.org/p/tempest-scenario-manager-cleanup

commit_message:
Remove handling of 'u' prefix

The prefix is no longer printed in Python 3.

In python 2
>>> print({u'foo': u'baa'})
{u'foo': u'baa'}
>>> print([u'foo', 'baa'])
[u'foo', 'baa']

In python 3
>>> print({u'foo': u'baa'})
{'foo': 'baa'}
>>> print([u'foo', 'baa'])
['foo', 'baa']

Change-Id: I30391cec53e425ee8cd0f94b31eb564098b47cb8

commit_message:
Add support for custom policies into the CLI

This is to ensure that we do not enforce "Server side" knowledge
 into the Client side library.

The policies available on the server of Nova API is only known by
 Nova and not by the client side librairies.  If the nova API
 developers decide to add other policies later down the train,
 this will enable them.  It also enable customers who implements
 their own policies on their Openstack instances.

There has been many upgrade to the policies and scheduler in the
recent years, a chunk of them to enable custom policies to be
registered by other librairies on the server-side.

Ref.
https://storyboard.openstack.org/#!/story/2008975
https://storyboard.openstack.org/#!/story/2008999
Change-Id: Ib6a6ddf0fa3ef39f2073bbc6ec2c740ae5dea2c9

commit_message:
Add support for custom policies into the CLI

This is to ensure that we do not enforce "Server side" knowledge
 into the Client side library.

The policies available on the server of Nova API is only known by
 Nova and not by the client side librairies.  If the nova API
 developers decide to add other policies later down the train,
 this will enable them.  It also enable customers who implements
 their own policies on their Openstack instances.

There has been many upgrade to the policies and scheduler in the
recent years, a chunk of them to enable custom policies to be
registered by other librairies on the server-side.

Ref.
https://storyboard.openstack.org/#!/story/2008975
https://storyboard.openstack.org/#!/story/2008999
Change-Id: Ib6a6ddf0fa3ef39f2073bbc6ec2c740ae5dea2c9

[{'created': '2022-03-21 17:38:36.000000000', 'message': 'chunkeddriver: use iterative json encoding

When dumping the json file, we were using `json.dumps` that
essentially duplicates the memory usage by joining the chunks of the
string.

This patch instead uses `json.dump` with a custom encoder to encode in
utf-8 each chunk, so they can be written separately instead of having
to hold the whole encoded string in memory.

Closes-Bug: #1965799

commit_message:
chunkeddriver: use iterative json encoding

When dumping the json file, we were using `json.dumps` that
essentially duplicates the memory usage by joining the chunks of the
string.

This patch instead uses `json.dump` with a custom encoder to encode in
utf-8 each chunk, so they can be written separately instead of having
to hold the whole encoded string in memory.

Closes-Bug: #1965799
Change-Id: Ia9214066db5baea50efb1e55f71b54e75e259cc5
Signed-off-by: David Caro <me@dcaro.es>

[{'created': '2022-03-31 17:59:07.000000000', 'message': "NVMe-oF: Fix encryption

Only LUKS v1 encrypted volumes will work as expected, and that's because
nova doesn't use the os-brick decryptors but uses libvirt directly.

The problem with non LUKS v1 encrypted volumes is that the connector is
not returning a symlink like os-brick and nova expects, so when creating
the device mapper and doing the symlink we kind of destroy the actual
device (i.e., /dev/nvme0n1) and when we disconnect the volume the Linux
nvme driver will not remove the device.

So we'll have a broken device under /dev, and when we try to attach the
next nvmeof device it will not be able to replace the broken device we
left behind (doesn't matter if it's the same volume or a different one).

From that point onwards we'll have troubles attaching nvme devices.

This patch changes the nvmeof connector to return symlinks when doing an
encrypted connection as expected by the rest of the flow (just like we
do in iSCSI and other connectors).

Instead of using a symlink created by udev during the creation of the
device we instead create our own symlink that reflects what the original
device name was.  This is necessary for the disconnect, for things like
flushing the right device.

Closes-Bug: #1964379
Change-Id: Idddd3131ecf883cab01954f612a2a7e82039d102
"}]
commit_message:
NVMe-oF: Fix encryption

Only LUKS v1 encrypted volumes will work as expected, and that's because
nova doesn't use the os-brick decryptors but uses libvirt directly.

The problem with non LUKS v1 encrypted volumes is that the connector is
not returning a symlink like os-brick and nova expects, so when creating
the device mapper and doing the symlink we kind of destroy the actual
device (i.e., /dev/nvme0n1) and when we disconnect the volume the Linux
nvme driver will not remove the device.

So we'll have a broken device under /dev, and when we try to attach the
next nvmeof device it will not be able to replace the broken device we
left behind (doesn't matter if it's the same volume or a different one).

From that point onwards we'll have troubles attaching nvme devices.

This patch changes the nvmeof connector to return symlinks when doing an
encrypted connection as expected by the rest of the flow (just like we
do in iSCSI and other connectors).

Instead of using a symlink created by udev during the creation of the
device we instead create our own symlink that reflects what the original
device name was.  This is necessary for the disconnect, for things like
flushing the right device.

Closes-Bug: #1964379
Change-Id: Idddd3131ecf883cab01954f612a2a7e82039d102

commit_message:
Fix duplicate object error messages

Fixed an issue where creation of duplicate listeners or members may have
not returned the correct error message to users.
The API would traceback with AttributeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'to_dict'

Made adjustments to patch for Python 2 compatibility in Train.

 Conflicts:
	octavia/api/v2/controllers/member.py
	octavia/api/v2/controllers/listener.py

commit_message:
Limit docutils to <0.19

docutils 0.19 deprecated frontend.OptionParser and in a later release
it will be replaced with an argparse.ArgumentParser based solution.
Till it is ready to avoid failing unit tests
(DockerReadmeTestCase.test_mentioned_latest_version and
DocstringsTestCase.test_all_plugins_have_docstrings) and unblock gate
cap docutils to <0.19

Change-Id: I2d82daa0d6d06fba8b386ac6a80a97cda6bc1630
Related-Bug: #1981194

commit_message:
Suppress 2 warnings from Docutils

The following 2 warnings do not require any modification of our code, so
we can silently hide them and wait for new release of docutils:

- The frontend.OptionParser class will be replaced by a subclass of
  argparse.ArgumentParser in Docutils 0.21 or later.
- The frontend.Option class will be removed in Docutils 0.21 or later.

Also, this commit temporary disables all dsvm job. They require a fix
for list-resources ansible role, but it would be nice to do that in a
separate change.

Change-Id: I82e794c3d12222db9380701e6923b6e065b596ac
Closes-Bug: 1981194

commit_message:
Control rally-openstack installed version

At the moment we don't have control what version of rally-openstack
is being installed. So we are installing latest version available in
PyPi. However rally package version is defined in
rally-openstack constraints.

With this patch we add variables to be able to adjust source of
rally-openstack as well as pick version for installation.

Needed-By: https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/openstack-ansible/+/847272
Change-Id: I8100dfd3544c0530815fb877b44b960d404f635b

It's very difficult to ensure that tasks are written without
run_once, expecting that they would be run with tripleo_free.
As tripleo_free does not ensure that the tasks are successfully
executed with run_once, let's go back to original ansible free

commit_message:
Modify run_once behavior of tripleo_free strategy

It's very difficult to ensure that tasks are written without
run_once, expecting that they would be run with tripleo_free.
As tripleo_free does not ensure that the tasks are successfully
executed with run_once, let's go back to original ansible free
strategy behavior of running it for all hosts.

Change-Id: I1c67885f553aee519466249ac056f75071014c24
Resolves: rhbz#2061393

commit_message:
Optimize _local_delete calls by compute unit tests

_fake_do_delete function from nova/tests/unit/compute/test_api.py is
called with reservations=None argument. This argument is no longer used
in _local_delete. Since_fake_do_delete function is not really used
because it only contains pass statement, we can replace it with no op
call implemented using lambda function.

Change-Id: Idf9686afeadc2d000c3bc255e809c914967a063f

commit_message:
Catch an exception in power off procedure

In libvirt driver, an exception of libvirt error may be thrown
when calling shutdown method.

This exception is caught by nobody, then the following retry
logic and the destroy method will be missed, causing the power
off procedure failure.

Catch this exception (as the retry logic does) to make the
procedure go on.

Change-Id: Icf9b15207a7e13333cf5640a5bce0e1082ecf4ec

This is the Zed milestone-2 release for castellan.
Clients and libraries following the cycle-with-intermediary release
model are encouraged to release each milestone to make sure updates
are made available.

If you are happy with the current release hash, please +1 this patch
and we will process a release. If you need to get some important
changes merged first, leave a -1 and update the patch with a new
commit hash to use once it is ready.

If a release is definitely not wanted at this time, please -1 and
leave a comment explaining that and we can abandon the patch.

Any patches with no response will be assumed to be OK and will be
processed by July 14th.

[{'created': '2022-07-12 06:41:16.000000000', 'message': "container: broaden the is_deleted method

Unlike `get_info` which just gets the object_count for the
current storage policy. So is only looking at a particularly small
scope. This patch makes the _is_deleted method more broad and checks to
see if the broker contains any objects.

It'll look at all storage_policies and any shard_ranges that are in
a state where they are responsible for their given namespace. Namely
those that are in SHARD_STATS_STATES.
If we find a object then we return False, ie it isn't deleted. This
allows the consistency engine to pick up and figure things out, be
it the sharder, replicator or reconciler.

Change-Id: Ib5c28bbdf6cd77df2df23e6618fcb72d7849b6d2
"}, {'created': '2022-07-12 07:11:35.000000000', 'message': "container: broaden is_deleted method by using empty

Unlike `get_info` which just gets the object_count for the
current storage policy. So is only looking at a particularly small
scope. This patch makes the _is_deleted method more broad and checks to
see if the broker contains any objects.

Turns out we already do a broader check in the broker.empty() method.
It's this method we use on a container DELETE to see if we can infact
delete the container, if it isn't empty, then we return a 409.

So why aren't we using the same thing in the is_delete check. The
is_delete check should check to see if the container is empty and take
the PUT and DELETE timestamps into account.

This patch set does just that. It uses `.empty()` for the empty check,
checking all storage polices and checks to see if the delete_timestamp >
put_timestamp.

The empty already also then checks the shard_usage for shard states in
the SHARD_STATS_STATES but only if it's a root container.

If we find a object then we return False, ie it isn't deleted. This
allows the consistency engine to pick up and figure things out, be
it the sharder, replicator or reconciler.

Change-Id: Ib5c28bbdf6cd77df2df23e6618fcb72d7849b6d2
"}]
commit_message:
container: broaden is_deleted method by using empty

Unlike `get_info` which just gets the object_count for the
current storage policy. So is only looking at a particularly small
scope. This patch makes the _is_deleted method more broad and checks to
see if the broker contains any objects.

Turns out we already do a broader check in the broker.empty() method.
It's this method we use on a container DELETE to see if we can infact
delete the container, if it isn't empty, then we return a 409.

So why aren't we using the same thing in the is_delete check. The
is_delete check should check to see if the container is empty and take
the PUT and DELETE timestamps into account.

This patch set does just that. It uses `.empty()` for the empty check,
checking all storage polices and checks to see if the delete_timestamp >
put_timestamp.

The empty already also then checks the shard_usage for shard states in
the SHARD_STATS_STATES but only if it's a root container.

If we find a object then we return False, ie it isn't deleted. This
allows the consistency engine to pick up and figure things out, be
it the sharder, replicator or reconciler.

Change-Id: Ib5c28bbdf6cd77df2df23e6618fcb72d7849b6d2

commit_message:
Allow customisation of stick-tables for each service.

A new variable "haproxy_stick_table" is added which allows a custom
stick-table to be supplied that is used as the default stick-table
for all haproxy back-ends.

In addition, the variable service.haproxy_stick_table can be defined
for each service to allow a unique stick-table to be supplied for
a particular service.

The old default stick-table definition is removed as there was no
use case defined for it in this role before. An example is added
to defaults/main.yml to show how the custom stick-table can be used
to rate-limit requests that generate 4xx responses which commonly
occur during vulnerability scanning or credential stuffing attacks.
There are many other uses for stick-tables, consult the HAProxy
documentation for details.

Change-Id: I50daba08c10f071157d6450ea2fa97df448f99ec

commit_message:
Control rally-openstack installed version

At the moment we don't have control what version of rally-openstack
is being installed. So we are installing latest version available in
PyPi. However rally package version is defined in
rally-openstack constraints.

With this patch we add variables to be able to adjust source of
rally-openstack as well as pick version for installation.

We set some jobs as non-voting to resolve circular dependency.

Change-Id: I8100dfd3544c0530815fb877b44b960d404f635b

revisions:
[{'created': '2022-01-14 18:38:46.000000000', 'message': 'Test resize with mem_page_size in flavor

These tests are meant to address issue [1]. It adds three new testcases:

 * test_hugepage_resize_keyword_large_to_small
 * test_hugepage_resize_explicit_pagesize_to_small
 * test_hugepage_resize_explicit_size_to_size

All three tests follow the same basic procedure, spawn a guest with a
flavor using hw:mem_page_size:<size_a>, resize the guest to a flavor
with a different size hw:mem_page_size:<size_b>, and then resize the
guest back to the original flavor. Throughout the tests XML checks are
conducted to ensure the page size is accurate for the present flavor.

Instead of trying to dynamically determine the hugepage sizes configured
on the computes, a new config parameter was added to define what
hugepage sizes are available on the host. To avoid dynamic ram
calculation sizes for the guest based on available hugepages, a guest
ram parameter was also added so users may define the size to use when
spawning guests.

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1831269

Change-Id: I5282df3b20c24a909f3b7bb97214206bc07e5b91

These tests are meant to address issue [1]. It adds three new testcases:

 * test_hugepage_resize_keyword_large_to_small
 * test_hugepage_resize_explicit_pagesize_to_small
 * test_hugepage_resize_explicit_size_to_size

All three tests follow the same basic procedure, spawn a guest with a
flavor using hw:mem_page_size:<size_a>, resize the guest to a flavor
with a different size hw:mem_page_size:<size_b>, and then resize the
guest back to the original flavor. Throughout the tests XML checks are
conducted to ensure the page size is accurate for the present flavor.

Instead of trying to dynamically determine the hugepage sizes configured
on the computes, a new config parameter was added to define what
hugepage sizes are available on the host. To avoid dynamic ram
calculation sizes for the guest based on available hugepages, a guest
ram parameter was also added so users may define the size to use when
spawning guests.

We also need a new job that has multiple hugepage sizes configured. We
cannot use our existing whitebox-devstack-multinode job because that
one runs tests that dynamically turn on file backed memory, which is
incompatible with hugepages. This commit adds tasks into job setup
that allows for the setup of hugepages.

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1831269

Depends-on: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/825011

Change-Id: I5282df3b20c24a909f3b7bb97214206bc07e5b91

commit_message:
Test resize with mem_page_size in flavor

These tests are meant to address issue [1]. It adds three new testcases:

 * test_hugepage_resize_keyword_large_to_small
 * test_hugepage_resize_explicit_pagesize_to_small
 * test_hugepage_resize_explicit_size_to_size

All three tests follow the same basic procedure, spawn a guest with a
flavor using hw:mem_page_size:<size_a>, resize the guest to a flavor
with a different size hw:mem_page_size:<size_b>, and then resize the
guest back to the original flavor. Throughout the tests XML checks are
conducted to ensure the page size is accurate for the present flavor.

Instead of trying to dynamically determine the hugepage sizes configured
on the computes, a new config parameter was added to define what
hugepage sizes are available on the host. To avoid dynamic ram
calculation sizes for the guest based on available hugepages, a guest
ram parameter was also added so users may define the size to use when
spawning guests.

We also need a new job that has multiple hugepage sizes configured. We
cannot use our existing whitebox-devstack-multinode job because that
one runs tests that dynamically turn on file backed memory, which is
incompatible with hugepages. This commit adds tasks into job setup
that allows for the setup of hugepages.

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1831269

Change-Id: I5282df3b20c24a909f3b7bb97214206bc07e5b91

commit_message:
setup.cfg: Replace dashes with underscores

Setuptools v54.1.0 introduces a warning that the use of
dash-separated options in 'setup.cfg' will not be supported
in a future version [1].
Get ahead of the issue by replacing the dashes with underscores.
Without this, we see 'UserWarning' messages
like the following on new enough
versions of setuptools:

  UserWarning: Usage of dash-separated 'description-file' will not be
  supported in future versions. Please use the underscore name
  'description_file' instead

[1] https://github.com/pypa/setuptools/commit/a2e9ae4cb

Change-Id: I4664cf66cd68526a81bb19ecb86f09ff0753f977

commit_message:
NetApp SolidFire: Fix race condition in delete cgsnapshot

A race condition in SolidFire API may occur between
"ListGroupSnapshots" and "DeleteGroupSnapshot" when called
concurrently, throwing API error "xSnapshotIDDoesNotExist". This
issue will commonly happen when multiple calls to delete
consistency group Snapshot are made.

This patch adds a coordination lock to serialize calls
to delete Consistency groups Snapshot, preventing them from
failing.

Change-Id: I6237cf9043f608a5f78ce6ef8eb0ef0e45cf95d4
Closes-Bug: #1791594

The SQLite in-memory databases have been great for testing but
as the swift DatabaseBroker's have become more complex, the limitations
of in memory databases are being reached. Mostly due
to the introduction of container sharding where a broker sometimes needs

Rather then rework the real broker logic to better support in-memory
testing, it's actually easier to just remove the in-memory broker tests

removed.

commit_message:
Remove :memory: from DatabaseBrokers and unittests

The SQLite in-memory databases have been great for testing but
as the swift DatabaseBroker's have become more complex, the limitations
of in memory databases are being reached. Mostly due
to the introduction of container sharding where a broker sometimes needs
to make multiple connections to the same database as the same time.

Rather then rework the real broker logic to better support in-memory
testing, it's actually easier to just remove the in-memory broker tests
and use a "real" broker in a tempdir. This allows us to better test how
brokers behave in real life, pending files and all.

This patch replaces all the :memory: brokers in the tests with real ones
placed in a tempdir. To achieve this, we new base unittest class `TestDBBase`
has been added that creates, cleans up and provides some helper methods
to manage the db path and location.

Further, all references to :memory: in the Database brokers have been
removed.

Change-Id: I5983132f776b84db634fef39c833d5cfdce11980

[{'created': '2022-07-11 05:14:53.000000000', 'message': 'ubuntu: more exact match on squashfs file

The functests are failing with

 sha256sum: bionic-server-cloudimg-amd64.squashfs.manifest: No such file or directory

I think what has happened here is that the SHA256 sums file being used
has got a new entry "bionic-server-cloudimg-amd64.squashfs.manifest"
which is showing up in a grep for
"bionic-server-cloudimg-amd64.squashfs".  sha256 then tries to also
check this hash, and has started failing.

To avoid this, add an EOL marker to the grep so it only matches the
exact filename.

Change-Id: Id5f134d772d56640990b5c7bf40739c21e2d8aa3
'}]
commit_message:
ubuntu: more exact match on squashfs file

The functests are failing with

 sha256sum: bionic-server-cloudimg-amd64.squashfs.manifest: No such file or directory

I think what has happened here is that the SHA256 sums file being used
has got a new entry "bionic-server-cloudimg-amd64.squashfs.manifest"
which is showing up in a grep for
"bionic-server-cloudimg-amd64.squashfs".  sha256 then tries to also
check this hash, and has started failing.

To avoid this, add an EOL marker to the grep so it only matches the
exact filename.

Change-Id: Id5f134d772d56640990b5c7bf40739c21e2d8aa3

commit_message:
Configure the oslo.concurrency lock_path

A recent change in os-brick [1], which is used by cinder backends,
requires external file locks. This patch adds support for configuring
the lock path, with a default value that matches the corresponding
lock paths used by other services that use os-brick (namely cinder
and nova).

[1] I6f7f7d19540361204d4ae3ead2bd6dcddb8fcd68

Closes-Bug: #1980539
Change-Id: I5ea6766656f4227a1c514777c03bbf78d4ac59cd
(cherry picked from commit 6f61ecd9c5b030817d0255fd8fd485722f9556f4)
(cherry picked from commit ba4ada0c70b31277b8569b71d40692b17c2a632b)

commit_message:
Debian/Ubuntu: Use tftpd-hpa instead of tftpd

The tftpd-hpa package possesses a number of bugfixes and enhancements
over the original tftpd package. Especially it supports the 'tsize'
which is required by PXE.

Change-Id: I41b95f80ed4d972a65f25541d2c5f4ae2df79d60
(cherry picked from commit 80307bece658a7bc6897cf5a57ca4eab3fa466cd)

commit_message:
Ubuntu: Use utf8mb3 charset in MySQL

... to fix the broken idempotency in litmus job. Current mysql/mariadb
in Ubuntu replaces utf8 with uft8mb3 automatically and this behavior
results in unexpected change in second run.

Depends-on: https://review.opendev.org/804365
Related-Bug: #1929073
Change-Id: I41a6fe11e8ab39a60b19299da18ee085a10dc202

commit_message:
Deprecate redundant DockerNovaMigrationSshdPort

Currently we have the following two parameters to control the tcp port
for ssh connection used by nova migration feature.

1) MigrationSshPort
This parameter determines the tcp port defined in ssh client
configuration and also the one allowed by firewall rule.

2) DockerNovaMigrationSshdPort
This parameter determines tcp port which sshd for nova migration
listens on.

This is very redundant, especially considering the fact that users
should update these two parameters consistently to change port number
from the default one.

This change deprecates the DockerNovaMigrationSshdPort parameter, so
that we can replace that by MigrationSshPort in a future release, and
provide only that single parameter.

Also, some constraints about port number has been added, to accept
a value within the valid range.

Change-Id: Ia80c8b8711cda4d6189051d75eb13967a44dc40d

commit_message:
upgrading subchart config only impacts subchart

This verifies that making a configuration change to one of Umbrella's
subcharts results in only the application (DaemonSet, Deployment or
StatefulSet) for that subchart being updated. No other subchart's
application should be updated.

This only validates subcharts from openstack-helm-infra.
Validating the remaining subcharts from openstack-helm will
be done in the future.

OpenStack Umbrella's default values for rabbitmq was configured
to use a host path. This is so rabbitmq retains its data
between StatefulSet changes. Otherwise components fail to authenticate
with rabbitmq after the rabbitmq pods have been recreated. The
OpenStack Umbrella Chart will use the `standard` storage class
by default since that's what is provisioned via minikube.

Change-Id: I8570e32e6ae03563037608d337f31066edf29755

commit_message:
Remove check_floating_ip_status & _associate_floating_ip methods

As tempest.scenario.manager was announced stable interface
in Tempest 27.0.0[1] it can be now reused in plugins.

Replaced methods:
	* _associate_floating_ip
	* check_floating_ip_status

Etherpad concerning this effort:
https://etherpad.opendev.org/p/tempest-scenario-manager-cleanup

The commit also bumps the minimal version of tempest in the
requirements to tempest>=27.0.0.

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/releasenotes/tempest/v27.0.0.html#release-notes-27-0-0

Change-Id: Ie17c1d9349e98ce016801bf47c1cb9dba18b51f6

Fix quota list command for non-admin users

Due to a logic error the all-projects header was being set if no
explicit project was being specified.

Closes-Bug: 1980942

subject: Ensure bootstrap packages are correctly installed
messages: [{'account_id': 28223, 'date': '2022-07-08 10:13:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Cherry Picked from branch master.'}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2022-07-08 10:35:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 30073, 'date': '2022-07-11 06:18:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 28223, 'date': '2022-07-11 14:07:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:\n\n(1 comment)'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2022-07-08 10:13:42.000000000', 'message': 'Ensure bootstrap packages are correctly installed

It may happen a package fails to properly install (especially for
openstack-selinux). Unfortunately, in such cases rpm will just output
some warning lost in the output, and will still exit with a success code
(0).

This patch allows to leverage the "--verify" option of RPM. If a package
spec file has a %verifyscript scriptlet, it will be called, and do
whatever is described in it.
In openstack-selinux case, it will ensure everything is actually
installed without issue[1].
If a package doesn't have the %verifyscript, rpm will just exit 0
without any error nor warning.

Note:
the failed_when condition allows to:
- protect against missing package (openvswitch)
- ensure we're actually failing on the %verifyscript
The second part is useful when we don't get the doc for package -
apparently, this is the case for python3-pyyaml, at least in CI
(molecule).

[1] https://review.rdoproject.org/r/c/openstack/openstack-selinux-distgit/+/43578

Change-Id: Iec1e79c9c1cbb6b7e5e7b768d425aab8270c1d89
(cherry picked from commit 2f29bfb7e01d94e42e5e6fcc9305f339d8d5efe4)
'}]
commit_message:
Ensure bootstrap packages are correctly installed

It may happen a package fails to properly install (especially for
openstack-selinux). Unfortunately, in such cases rpm will just output
some warning lost in the output, and will still exit with a success code
(0).

This patch allows to leverage the "--verify" option of RPM. If a package
spec file has a %verifyscript scriptlet, it will be called, and do
whatever is described in it.
In openstack-selinux case, it will ensure everything is actually
installed without issue[1].
If a package doesn't have the %verifyscript, rpm will just exit 0
without any error nor warning.

Note:
the failed_when condition allows to:
- protect against missing package (openvswitch)
- ensure we're actually failing on the %verifyscript
The second part is useful when we don't get the doc for package -
apparently, this is the case for python3-pyyaml, at least in CI
(molecule).

[1] https://review.rdoproject.org/r/c/openstack/openstack-selinux-distgit/+/43578

Change-Id: Iec1e79c9c1cbb6b7e5e7b768d425aab8270c1d89
(cherry picked from commit 2f29bfb7e01d94e42e5e6fcc9305f339d8d5efe4)

commit_message:
ibm_storage: Remove unused _get_os_type method

platform.dist() doesn't exist on Python 3.8+, so this
no longer works.  This method is not called by any
other code.

Change-Id: I97b000ad8eb2bf63aaa0bb110be6ca39b8359a94

commit_message:
ContainerBroker: modify determination of object_count

A container is considered deleted (ContainerBroker.is_deleted() ==
True) if its delete_timestamp is greater than its put_timestamp and it
is 'empty'.  Previously, for an UNSHARDED container, 'empty' was
determined by testing that the container DB object_count was
zero. However, the container may in fact be in the process of sharding
and have shard ranges cleaved from other replicas of the container
which have non-zero object_count. In this case the apparently empty DB
should not be considered deleted.

This patch therefore modifies the algorithm for determining the
container object_count: if a container DB is in state UNSHARDED or
SHARDING and has zero object_count, then the sum of shard range
object_counts will be reported instead of the DB object_count. This
will make no difference when the container is genuinely empty
(i.e. all shard ranges have been emptied) but will prevent apparently
empty DBs with populated shard_ranges being considered deleted.

Note that the sum of shard range object counts used is restricted to
shard ranges in ACTIVE, SHARDING, SHRINKING i.e. the same as used when
reporting object_count for a DB in SHARDED state.

Co-Authored-By: Matthew Oliver <matt@oliver.net.au>
Change-Id: I84a918f1c0de6fc61f66a7393c10c84e420729e4

commit_message:
Move bandit requirements to tox.ini

This makes bandit requirements work like our
pylint requirements.  (Neither are handled
in the typical way by openstack/requirements.)

This prevents needless installation of bandit
for each unit test job run.

Change-Id: I513de53520a4531067cea4e7a225fb1ad2e9ba06

commit_message:
upgrading an OSH subchart config only impacts subchart

This verifies that making a configuration change to one of Umbrella's
subcharts results in only the application (DaemonSet, Deployment or
StatefulSet) for that subchart being updated. No other subchart's
application should be updated.

This only validates subcharts from openstack-helm.
Validating the remaining subcharts from openstack-helm-infra has
been done in another commit.

Change-Id: I649dde64313dfaaa7440c86fd50c3882874bf122

commit_message:
[WIP] Added lifecycle management isolation testing to OpenStack Umbrella
chart

    Gate scripts to test the changes submitted to OpenStack Umbrella chart. These scripts will upgrade umbrella chart with test cases (changes) to a sub-chart and ensures that this upgrade is not affecting other sub-charts.

Change-Id: I1412e07c88675aeb431b9e284df32f79e559d367

Designate: Add common task for httpd config files

This change adds the common tasks to designate-api container image
build, to ensure Listen directive is disabled in httpd config files,
because now the container includes the httpd package.

commit_message:
Glance: Test backend classes with api class

The tripleo::profile::base::glance::backend::* are designed to be used
together with the tripleo::profile::base::glance::api class.
This change ensures the backend classes are tested with the api class
included. This solves the following error we see after the change
4b4d7d9a5a9a1654dd9b59891f934cfac75501a0 was merged to puppet-glance.

Could not find resource 'Service[glance-api]' for relationship from
'Anchor[swift::service::end]'

Change-Id: Ie8c7a7c7b092f501bfc7f4fd3d45b5a6118fcf50

"}, {'created': '2022-04-20 05:45:07.000000000', 'message': "Add (de)serialisze_v2 via RingSerialization classes

This patch also changes the way v2 serialization/deserialization works by
breaking it down into RingSerialization classes that handle dealing with
different types of blob/indexes.

All RingSerialization classes are based of the RingSerializeBase class
which provides a serialize and deserialize method. As well as the
index_name. When concrete RingSerialization classes are made, we
register them with the base class class method function decorator, to
build up a map of index_names to classes which allows us to easily walk
through the RingReader's index and serialize or deserialize the
requested section. Ie:

  @RingSerializeBase.register()
  class RingSerializeMetadata(RingSerializeBase):

It is also defining a constant:

  RING_SERIALIZATION_INDEXES = ('swift/metadata', 'swift/devs',
                                'swift/replica2part2dev')

Because we'd want a way for telling what particular indexes to load up
in the ring. This might seem like overkill in engineering, but this is a
stepping stone to allowing us to store the builder components in the ring.
And should help us reuse and tell what components we want in the builder
and the ring.

Change-Id: If086817d5f3d02e62d9c504373419225292e0651

commit_message:
Add (de)serialize_v2 via RingSerialization classes

This patch also changes the way v2 serialization/deserialization works by
breaking it down into RingSerialization classes that handle dealing with
different types of blob/indexes.

All RingSerialization classes are based of the RingSerializeBase class
which provides a serialize and deserialize method, as well as the
index_name. When concrete RingSerialization classes are made, we
register them with the base class class method function decorator, to
build up a map of index_names to classes which allows us to easily walk
through the RingReader's index and serialize or deserialize the
requested section. Ie:

  @RingSerializeBase.register()
  class RingSerializeMetadata(RingSerializeBase):

It is also defining a constant:

  RING_SERIALIZATION_INDEXES = ('swift/metadata', 'swift/devs',
                                'swift/replica2part2dev')

Because we'd want a way for telling what particular indexes to load up
in the ring. This might seem like overkill in engineering, but this is a
stepping stone to allowing us to store the builder components in the ring.
And should help us reuse and tell what components we want in the builder
and the ring.

Change-Id: If086817d5f3d02e62d9c504373419225292e0651

commit_message:
Fix TLS*_METHOD for old pyopenssl releases

The TLS_METHOD constant was introduced in pyopenssl 21.0.0 [0], but some
older Octavia branches (from train to victoria) still use older releases
(19.1.0 for victoria) and then don't support it. Switch back to the
previous the SSL methods if the new constanst doesn't exist.

[0] https://github.com/pyca/pyopenssl/commit/5dc698861c91b4aa83b284b282c0e91cdcee49a3

Change-Id: Ib0eeb1136c168fcc32326f4ed8b008fb7f193a30

commit_message:
Add missing oslo_limit options

Glance now depends on the oslo.limit library to support the unified
quota[1], but parameters of the library are still missing from
glance-api.conf.

This change ensures the parameter of the oslo.limit library are
included in glance-api.conf generated by oslo-config-generator.

[1] 06e6542f153a1ba197361f3f8cb0010c7d2d4285

Closes-Bug: #1946100
Change-Id: I56a2a9d8184f50624239b90dd9bef671c195fb90

commit_message:
[Wallaby-only] Fixes for wallaby molecule jobs

Currently CS8 master dlrn builder is stopped
and removed in future. test_deps role uses master
branch to configure repo and since there will be
no master packages for cs8. The jobs will fail.

Switching it to wallaby release fixes the issue.

Currently cs9 molecule config backport patches
are blocked due to job freeze issue
https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/tripleo-ansible/+/848104/3#message-31598572fd80f4000d3b2e9ff4201dd5e30fc20b
as cs9 content provider[1][2] does not run on molecule changes.

Overriding the irrelvant files, fixes the issue.
[1]. https://opendev.org/openstack/tripleo-ci/src/commit/28ea0202e38945f2a2a88f42c6c15ef8b39e27f6/zuul.d/standalone-jobs.yaml#L119
[2]. https://opendev.org/openstack/tripleo-ci/src/commit/28ea0202e38945f2a2a88f42c6c15ef8b39e27f6/zuul.d/standalone-jobs.yaml#L57

Signed-off-by: Chandan Kumar (raukadah) <chkumar@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I7e213de59a6982e13546da7e83b807d30aab8166

commit_message:
broker: Ensure request-id key is present

When an unexpected error is encountered, the broker response sent
back to the requesting application lacks the request-id key so
can't be matched on the client end of the relation to a specific
request.

Ensure that this is set in all situations including unexpected
error.

Change-Id: I327b406a9fbbe1058e934d0029404f56fc6b2a2e
Related-Bug: 1872043

commit_message:
Bump minimum python requirement to 3.8

Cinder has already removed support for python 3.6 and now requires
python >= 3.8 . This change updates the testing runtime accordingly.

Because CentOS Stream 8 has only Python 3.6 available, this change
bumps OS version to 9 which has Python 3.9.

Change-Id: Idf16c3ccb6b3fe6800213dc3e28b5113bcf36c4e

commit_message:
Set sensible nf_conntrack_max value in amphora

This sets the values of nf_conntrack_max and nf_conntrack_expect_max to
sensible values. Previously, the default values set by the kernel were
used, which limited net.netfilter.nf_conntrack_max to 32768. On the
other hand, Octavia sets nf_conntrack_buckets to 125000. A value of
nf_conntrack_max lower than half of that makes no sense.

The new values are calculated using the formula for the default value
in the kernel [1]:

nf_conntrack_max = nf_conntrack_buckets
nf_conntrack_expect_max = nf_conntrack_buckets / 256

[1]: https://www.kernel.org/doc/Documentation/networking/nf_conntrack-sysctl.rst

Story: 2010050
Task: 45460

commit_message:
Update python testing as per zed cycle teting runtime

In Zed cycle, we have dropped the python 3.6/3.7[1] testing
and its support. Moving the py36 job to py38 based as well as
updating the python classifier also to reflect the same.

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/reference/runtimes/zed.html

commit_message:
Set sensible nf_conntrack_max value in amphora

This sets the values of nf_conntrack_max and nf_conntrack_expect_max to
sensible values. Previously, the default values set by the kernel were
used, which limited net.netfilter.nf_conntrack_max to 32768. On the
other hand, Octavia sets nf_conntrack_buckets to 125000. A value of
nf_conntrack_max lower than half of that makes no sense.

The new values are calculated using the formula for the default value
in the kernel [1]:

nf_conntrack_max = nf_conntrack_buckets
nf_conntrack_expect_max = nf_conntrack_buckets / 256

[1]: https://www.kernel.org/doc/Documentation/networking/nf_conntrack-sysctl.rst

commit_message:
Update to build using charmcraft

Due to a build problem with the reactive plugin, this change falls back
on overriding the steps and doing a manual build, but it also ensures
the CI system builds the charm using charmcraft.  Changes:

- add a build-requirements.txt
- modify charmcraft.yaml
- modify osci.yaml
    -> indicate build with charmcraft
- modify tox.ini
    -> tox -e build does charmcraft build/rename
    -> tox -e build-reactive does the reactive build
- modify bundles to use the <charm>.charm artifact in tests.
  and fix deprecation warning re: prefix
- tox inception to enable tox -e func-test in the CI
- Pin everything in wheelhouse.txt for bionic and focal support.
  This will need updating when the charm channels are created.

Change-Id: I6be651732c1778e29c7cbe2bf767c60ceec356eb

commit_message:
Add wait_for_migration_status function

Keep polling for instance status, if it is found in success_status
check whether source and destination hypvervisors are different or not.
Migration is considered successful they are different.
If both are same, migration is reported failed.

The error_status holds 'shutoff' state as well to check
failure of cold migration. Instance should endup in 'verify_resize'
state after cold migration.

Signed-off-by: Yadnesh Kulkarni <ykulkarn@redhat.com>
Change-Id: Ieb4241f0903ea4b3bd76720feb1126ecb914648e

commit_message:
Make instance reset-state an interactive operation

Ask for a confirmation from user while resetting the state of an instance
with a warning stating that this operation would make changes to the database.
Operation would be confirmed only if user accepts it else no action will be taken.

Signed-off-by: Yadnesh Kulkarni <ykulkarn@redhat.com>
Change-Id: Ibc1c2e3fbfb5b8c789be8aca2838056c292d9aae

messages:
[{'account_id': 32240, 'date': '2021-01-28 14:02:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 32240, 'date': '2021-01-29 02:12:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 32240, 'date': '2021-01-30 08:11:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 32240, 'date': '2021-02-03 15:17:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 32240, 'date': '2021-02-04 08:44:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 15334, 'date': '2021-04-16 11:54:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I thought I'd left comments here already, but I clearly didn't. This isn't an ideal solution. Nova has the ability to auto-confirm resizes (enabled via the '[compute] resize_confirm_window' option). As such, this introduces the chance of a race between the client checking the server status and the server auto-confirming the resize.

I've been trying to think of other solutions. The first one that jumped to mind was to check that the host changed, but that won't work because you can cold migrate and resize to the same host if you enable '[DEFAULT] allow_resize_to_same_host' or if your host reports the 'COMPUTE_SAME_HOST_COLD_MIGRATE' (for the cold migrate case only). A better option would be to poll the server migrations API (exposed via 'nova server-migration-list') or migrations API (exposed via 'nova migration-list'). The latter is available longer so it might be wiser. The only issue for this would be that iirc migrations requests that are rejected early in the process are not recorded here. That should be okay though. You just wait for a given period for the migration to appear and if it doesn't, assume it has failed.

Thoughts? Would that approach work? I don't have a deployment to hand rn but I could certainly spin one up if necessary to try this out"}, {'account_id': 32240, 'date': '2022-07-11 12:22:19.000000000', 'content': 'Removed reviewer <GERRIT_ACCOUNT_9816>.'}, {'account_id': 32240, 'date': '2022-07-11 12:22:22.000000000', 'content': 'Removed reviewer <GERRIT_ACCOUNT_30073>.'}, {'account_id': 32240, 'date': '2022-07-11 12:22:58.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Failed resize reported as complete

If resize operation fails, cli reports it as completed when using
"--wait" to monitor the progress. If resize is successful then
instance should move into "verify_resize" and not stay in "active".
So move "active" from success_status to error_status.

Closes-Bug: #2006973
Signed-off-by: Yadnesh Kulkarni <ykulkarn@redhat.com>
Change-Id: Ifd4875f1fac64284072265ae1cf8b964743960d8

commit_message:
Add smartmontools package to DIB image

This package includes smartctl, which is necessary for ATA secure erase
disk cleaning.

Without this package, IPA will fall back to shredding ATA devices, and
you will lose hours of your life. Worse, until
https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/ironic-python-agent/+/847591, the
lack of smartctl was silently ignored.

Change-Id: I6952b833e0be4a47e45e9c4d4459956093628b6a
(cherry picked from commit 57f50f7e10e0043d7aa1e860b72f98211eef4567)

commit_message:
New Quota System

Cinder quotas have been a constant pain for operators and cloud users.
This spec proposes a new quota system to resolve inconsistencies in
tracking quota usage.

This spec proposes reduce the usage of the reservations to a minimum and
have 2 quota drivers, one that leverages the DB engine to dynamically
count resources and another that stores the in-use and reserved counters
in the DB similarly to what we do today.

Change-Id: I3773be238a9edfc971d2b81135b23abfd3c974d7
Implements: blueprint count-resource-to-check-quota

commit_message:
Failed instance migration reported as complete

If instance migration operation fails, cli reports it as complete when
using "--wait" to monitor it's progress. Use "wait_for_migration_status"
which determines the success of migration by comparing the source and
destination hypervisor of the instance.

Depends-on: https://review.opendev.org/773877
Signed-off-by: Yadnesh Kulkarni <ykulkarn@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I47b4aea45506accd546955587c550272f8af6294

commit_message:
Add element reset-bls-entries to overcloud images

This is an element which will run a script on first boot to rename
`/boot/loader/entries` filenames to match the new value of
`/etc/machine-id`. This is required for `grub2-mkconfig` calls to
incorporate existing values in the boot loader entry files.

Depends-On: I354aeabed6d2993ae600b86381a7b625ca7f89dc
Closes: rhbz#2073855
Change-Id: I1726ab71fe1ff84bc35237a3a92d48090de7b0ad
(cherry picked from commit 7b786c0c37aba7076ee35f2ef04e8d0e13e6d6f0)

commit_message:
inspector: Prevent use of noauth in multi-region setup

In a multi-region environment without a local keystone, we should still
use authentication.

Change-Id: I9df0ddf6e0d56f0817256b07ae0a0a7021209663
(cherry picked from commit 3d65a160d93558a33c36b74deb4e92ec4a6d94bb)
